      <h1>Josh</h1>
      <p>What can I say about Justin and our whirlwind, eleven year long romance? I love him as much as the day I first met him, and yet I keep finding new reasons to cherish him.</p>

      <p>In 2002, when I first laid eyes on Justin, I knew I had found someone special. I was just out of high school and still very awkward, not used to what college had to offer, and I was concerned I wouldn't find someone that suited me -- but the moment I met him I knew I had found a kindred soul. Handsome, intelligent, and incredibly funny, I couldn't believe my luck.</p>

      <p>Back then, us marrying seemed like an impossibility: and to be honest I found the idea rather silly anyway. "Marriage is something for the straight world," I told myself. And anyway the word itself doesn't mean anything, or so it seemed to me. But leaving the legal benefits aside, there's a certain depth of relationship that having a husband communicates. And then, before we knew it, the winds of change blew in amazing new legislation: suddenly gay couples were getting married all over America. And we figured, why not us?</p>

      <p>We weren't first in line to be married, neither of us got down on a knee, and we didn't have an engagement. But that suited us fine -- we knew we were going to be wedded just the same. And finally, after years of waiting, we decided to make our dream a reality. We travelled to New York City and on the night of October 20th 2012, witnessed by our families, we signed into law what we knew already: that we would be together the rest of our lives.</p>

      <p>It's been a year of wedded bliss, and while our marriage has been wonderful, we realized we hadn't yet had the wedding! So we'd like to invite you to Chicago on October 12th, 2013 to celebrate our wedding and our marriage. With our friends and family together, we'll celebrate our union and also have a totally awesome time.</p>
    </div>

    <div class='justin'>
