      <h1>Justin</h1>
      <p>It was early 2002. The nation was at the brink of war, and yet in the turmoil two hearts found one another.</p>

      <p>I am very fortunate that Josh came into my life.  We were both young, bright eyed students at the University of Chicago in 2002 who instantly felt a connection over the sort of things teenagers bond over: computers, games, and movies.  At a time when things felt very uncertain, with looming wars overseas and the "culture wars" raging here, we found something that was certain - we were in love.</p>

      <p>As the seasons changed, so did we, cheering the victory of Lawrence v. Texas, bemoaning bitter presidential elections where gay-rights were used to divide the nation, and weathering our first, awkward jobs out of college.  Throughout we had the support of our loving families, who have come to accept their new sons with open arms.  In those early days, the words "I do" felt so impossibly far away, but a lot can change in a decade.  Economies can crumble just as you are ready to buy a home, war can break out less than 50 miles away from where you are staying abroad, and, as sea and temperature levels rise, Chicago starts to seem a nicer and nicer place to stay.  The one thing that hasn't changed is that we are still very much in love.</p>

      <p>When civil-unions suddenly passed in the State of Illinois, we were stunned.  While other couples may have planned romantic proposals with rings and knees, we just looked at each other in our living room and asked, "We're doing this, right?"  We weren't the same people from a decade before, but there was never any doubt what the other would say.  However, with elections looming in November, we weren't sure how long our opportunity would last.  So on October 20th, 2012, in New York City, we signed a marriage license witnessed by our families.  Now, a year later, we'd like our friends to come celebrate eleven years of happiness together in Chicago.  In the coming decades, a lot of things can change, but at least there's one constant: Justin and Josh are in love.</p>
